OL,4,CGlobal heating: Study shows impact of
OL,5,C'climate racism' in US
OL,6, A new study says that black people
OL,7, living in most US cities are subject to
OL,8, double the level of heat stress as
OL,9, their white counterparts.
OL,11,FThe researchers say the differences
OL,12,Fwere not explained by poverty but by
OL,13,Fhistoric racism and segregation.
OL,15,FAs a result, people of colour more
OL,16,Fgenerally, live in areas with fewer
OL,17,Fgreen spaces and more buildings and
OL,18,Froads.
OL,20,FThese exacerbate the impacts of rising
OL,21,Ftemperatures and a changing climate.
